<section class="section section--alt" id="qbo-feat-invoices-definition">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">In plain terms</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">QuickBooks Online invoicing, plainly.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>An invoice is a bill you send a customer for work delivered, and in QuickBooks Online it does two jobs at once. On the surface, it&rsquo;s a branded document &mdash; built from your products and services, addressed to a customer, carrying payment terms and a due date &mdash; that you email or share as a link, optionally with a Pay Now button so the customer can pay online. Underneath, the moment you create it, QuickBooks Online records the revenue and books the amount as <a href="/glossary/accounts-receivable/">accounts receivable</a>: money owed to you but not yet collected.</p>
      <p>That invoice stays open until you record the customer&rsquo;s payment and apply it to that specific invoice, which clears the receivable. Get that loop right &mdash; clean products and services behind every invoice, payments applied to the invoices they pay, deposits matched to the bank &mdash; and the AR aging report tells you exactly who owes what. Get it loose &mdash; payments unapplied, recorded twice, or stranded in Undeposited Funds &mdash; and both the reconciliation and the receivable stop telling the truth. The setup and that ongoing discipline are where an independent ProAdvisor firm works; an Intuit account, login, billing, or QuickBooks Payments fee question stays with Intuit.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

